message: Few? 14,785 (combining 11,507 German and 3,278 Italian Americans together) is A LOT. That number doesn't even include the 4,058 German Latin Americans and 288 Italian Latin Americans interned alongside them. Thousands of non-German family members of those interned also chose (voluntarily) to go to the camps.
It was stated earlier in the article that there were 37 women passengers. Adding the 2 stewardesses, we get 39 women.
